menu "BB HTTP Server"

config BB_HTTP_AUTOSTART
    bool "Auto-start HTTP server from bb_registry_init()"
    default y
    help
        When enabled, bb_registry_init() calls bb_http_server_start() automatically
        after the PRE_HTTP tier and before the regular route-registration tier.
        Disable if the application manages server startup itself (e.g. after CORS
        or OpenAPI configuration that must precede server start).


config BB_HTTP_MAX_URI_HANDLERS_MIN
    int "Minimum max_uri_handlers floor"
    default 32
    help
      Floor for auto-sized max_uri_handlers. Auto-size = sum(registry order)
      + fixed overhead (preflight + asset slack + safety). Final cap is
      max(auto-size, this floor).

config BB_HTTP_MAX_URI_HANDLERS_OVERRIDE
    int "Force max_uri_handlers to a specific value (0 = auto)"
    default 0
    help
      Non-zero forces this exact value, bypassing auto-sizing.

config BB_HTTP_MAX_OPEN_SOCKETS
    int "Maximum concurrent HTTP sockets"
    default 5
    range 4 16
    help
      ESP-IDF httpd reserves 3 of these for internal control sockets, so
      the effective client capacity is N-3. The IDF default is 7 (= 4
      client slots), which is too low when SSE log streaming + web UI
      page loads + occasional OTA upload run concurrently — lru_purge
      silently drops the oldest socket (often the SSE stream). Default
      5 (= 2 client slots) is a safe lower bound aligning with the most-
      restrictive realistic LWIP socket pool (LWIP=8 → cap=5); raise for
      fleets with many simultaneous clients.

config BB_HTTP_RECV_WAIT_TIMEOUT_S
    int "Per-recv socket timeout (seconds)"
    default 10
    help
      Maximum time httpd waits on a single recv() before returning
      timeout. OTA push compensates with a 30-retry loop (so 10s gives
      300s total stall budget). SSE streams bypass this via setsockopt
      after async handoff. Lower values reduce the window in which a
      stalled client holds a socket against the BB_HTTP_MAX_OPEN_SOCKETS
      cap.

config BB_HTTP_SEND_WAIT_TIMEOUT_S
    int "Per-send socket timeout (seconds)"
    default 10
    help
      Maximum time httpd waits on a single send() before returning
      timeout. See BB_HTTP_RECV_WAIT_TIMEOUT_S.

config BB_HTTP_TASK_CORE_ID
    int "HTTP server task core affinity (-1 = no affinity, 0 = CPU0, 1 = CPU1)"
    default -1
    range -1 1
    help
      Pins the esp_http_server worker task to a specific core. The IDF
      default (tskNO_AFFINITY) lets the worker land on either CPU, which
      can starve under contention with a high-priority single-core busy
      loop on the same CPU (e.g. a SHA mining hot loop). Pin off the
      hot-loop core to keep HTTP responsive.

config BB_HTTP_LWIP_RESERVE
    int "Sockets reserved for non-httpd usage (stratum, mDNS, transient outbound)"
    default 3
    range 1 6
    help
      bb_http caps httpd's max_open_sockets at CONFIG_LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS minus
      this value, so the remaining sockets stay available for stratum TCP,
      mDNS UDP, and any transient outbound HTTP (bb_http_client, bb_ota_pull,
      bb_update_check). Default 3 matches the original hardcoded behavior.

      Consumers with tighter actual non-httpd usage can lower this to give
      httpd more headroom for parallel-fetch UIs. Raising it carves off more
      slots for outbound work at httpd's expense.

endmenu
